sel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Udo.","South German:","variant of <b>Häusel</b>, a diminutive of   Haus  , a nickname for someone in a small house."]},{"name":"Hausmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Gunther, Arno, Benno, Berthold, Dietmar, Hans, Helmut, Jutta, Kurt, Lieselotte, Monika.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>hūs</i> ‘house’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, German <i>Haus</i> + <i>Mann</i>. In the Middle Ages the majority of the population lived in cottages or huts rather than houses, and in most cases this name probably indicates the steward of a great house or someone who had some other connection with the largest and most important building in a settlement. In some cases it may indicate a householder, steward at a castle, or the watchman on a tower. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   Haushalter  ."]},{"name":"Hauss","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Pierre.","German: variant of   Haus  . This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine)."]},{"name":"Hause","meanings":["German: variant of   Haus  ."]}]},{"name":"Gertrud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>gēr</i>, <i>gār</i> ‘spear’ + <i>þrūþ</i> ‘strength’; the name of two famous 13th-century nuns of the Cistercian Abbey of Helfta near Eisleben, whose spiritual writings had a great influence."],"variants":[{"name":"Gertraud","meanings":["from <i>gēr</i>, <i>gār</i> ‘spear’ + <i>þrūþ</i> ‘strength’; the name of two famous 13th-century nuns of the Cistercian Abbey of Helfta near Eisleben, whose spiritual writings had a great influence."]},{"name":"Gertraut","meanings":["from <i>gēr</i>, <i>gār</i> ‘spear’ + <i>þrūþ</i> ‘strength’; the name of two famous 13th-century nuns of the Cistercian Abbey of Helfta near Eisleben, whose spiritual writings had a great influence."]}]}],"l